WEBVTT

00:22.840 --> 00:29.180
CHAPTER XXIII A

00:29.180 --> 00:38.980
Splendid midsummer shone over England, skies so pure, suns so radiant, as were then seen

00:38.980 --> 00:47.640
in long succession, seldom favour, even singly, our wave-girt land.

00:48.640 --> 00:55.420
It was as if a band of Italian days had come from the south like a flock of glorious passenger

00:56.140 --> 01:03.820
and lighted to rest them on the cliffs of Albion. The hay was all got in, the fields

01:03.820 --> 01:12.440
round Thornfield were green and shorn, the roads white and baked, the trees were in their dark

01:12.440 --> 01:21.740
prime, hedge and wood, full-leaved and deeply tinted, contrasted well with the sunny hue

01:21.740 --> 01:29.960
of the cleared meadows between. On Midsummer Eve Adele, weary with gathering wild strawberries

01:29.960 --> 01:36.080
in Hay Lane half the day, had gone to bed with the sun. I watched her drop asleep,

01:36.080 --> 01:44.780
and when I left her I sought the garden. It was now the sweetest hour of the 24,

01:45.500 --> 01:54.440
day its fervid fires had wasted, and dew fell cool on Panting Plain and Scorched Summit.

01:55.920 --> 02:03.920
Where the sun had gone down in simple state, pure of the pomp of clouds spread a solemn

02:03.920 --> 02:12.440
purple burning with the light of red jewel and furnace flame at one point. On one hill peak,

02:12.440 --> 02:19.200
and extending high and wide, soft and still, softer over half heaven,

02:19.780 --> 02:28.160
East had its own charm or fine deep blue, and its own modest gem a casino and solitary star.

02:28.520 --> 02:33.220
Soon it would boast the moon, but she was yet beneath the horizon.

02:34.560 --> 02:41.640
I walked a while on the pavement, but a subtle, well-known scent, that of a cigar,

02:41.640 --> 02:49.720
stole from some window. I saw the library casement open at hand breadth. I knew I might be watched

02:49.720 --> 02:59.220
thence, so I went part into the orchard. No nook in the grounds more sheltered and more Eden-like.

02:59.740 --> 03:07.080
It was full of trees, it bloomed with flowers. A very high wall shut it out from the court

03:07.080 --> 03:12.740
on one side. On the other a beach avenue screamed it from the lawn.

03:13.640 --> 03:21.640
At the bottom was a sunk fence. Its sole separation from lonely fields a winding walk

03:21.640 --> 03:28.200
bordered with laurels and terminating in a giant horse chestnut, circled at the base by a seat,

03:28.600 --> 03:35.160
led down to the fence. Here one could wander unseen. While such honeydew fell,

03:35.160 --> 03:43.080
such silence rained, such gloaming gathered, I felt as if I could haunt such shade for ever.

03:43.360 --> 03:50.100
But in threading the flower and fruit parterres at the upper part of the enclosure,

03:50.520 --> 03:56.940
enticed there by the light, the now rising moon cast on this more open quarter,

03:56.940 --> 04:06.940
my step is stayed, not by sound, not by sight, but once more by a warning fragrance.

04:08.140 --> 04:16.320
Sweet brier and southern wood, jasmine, pink and rose have long been yielding their evening

04:16.790 --> 04:27.940
of incense. This new scent is neither of shrub nor flower. It is, I know it well. It is Mr.

04:28.180 --> 04:38.170
Rochester's cigar. I look round and I listen. I see trees laden with ripening fruit. I hear a

04:38.170 --> 04:48.690
gale warbling in a wood half a mile off. No moving form is visible. No coming step audible,

04:49.290 --> 04:57.610
but that perfume increases. I must flee. I make for the wicket leading to the shrubbery,

04:57.810 --> 05:06.450
and I see Mr. Rochester entering. I step aside into the ivy recess. He will not stay long.

05:06.450 --> 05:12.870
He will soon return whence he came, and if I sit still he will never see me.

05:13.550 --> 05:22.050
But no, even tide is as pleasant to him as to me, and this antique garden as attractive.

05:22.210 --> 05:29.870
And he strolls on, now lifting the gooseberry tree branches to look at the fruit, large as plums,

05:29.870 --> 05:34.730
with which they are laden, now taking a ripe cherry from the wall,

05:35.090 --> 05:42.850
now stooping towards a knot of flowers either to inhale their fragrance or to admire the dew

05:42.850 --> 05:59.850
beads on their petals. A great moth goes humming by me. It alights on a plant at Mr. Rochester's

05:59.850 --> 06:09.530
thought I, and he is occupied too. Perhaps if I walk softly I can slip away unnoticed.

06:10.650 --> 06:18.970
I trod on an edging of turf that the crackle of the pebbly gravel might not betray me.

06:19.710 --> 06:25.650
He was standing among the beds at a yard or two distance from where I had to pass.

06:26.210 --> 06:29.250
The moth apparently engaged him.

06:29.710 --> 06:36.570
I shall get by very well, I meditated, as I crossed his shadow thrown long over the garden

06:36.570 --> 06:42.590
by the moon, not yet risen high. He said quietly, without turning,

06:44.150 --> 06:47.250
Jane, come and look at this fellow.

06:48.210 --> 06:55.630
I had made no noise. He had not eyes behind. Could his shadow feel?

06:55.650 --> 06:59.690
I started at first, and then I approached him.

07:00.990 --> 07:07.550
Look at his wings, said he. He reminds me rather of a West Indian insect.

07:08.210 --> 07:13.870
One does not often see so large and gay a night-rover in England.

07:14.850 --> 07:16.790
There he has flown.

07:17.690 --> 07:25.130
The moth roamed away. I was sheepishly retreating also, but Mr. Rochester followed me,

07:25.130 --> 07:27.970
and when we reached the wicket, he said,

07:28.910 --> 07:34.310
Turn back. On so lovely a night it is ashamed to sit in the house,

07:34.530 --> 07:41.230
and surely no one can wish to go to bed while sunset is thus at meeting with moonrise.

07:42.630 --> 07:49.410
It is one of my faults that though my tongue is sometimes prompt enough as an answer,

07:49.970 --> 07:54.570
there are times when it sadly fails me in framing an excuse.

07:54.570 --> 08:03.630
And always the lapse occurs at some crisis, when a facile word or plausible pretext is

08:03.630 --> 08:08.110
specially wanting to get me out of painful embarrassment.

08:09.090 --> 08:15.470
I did not like to walk at this hour alone with Mr. Rochester in the shadowy orchard,

08:15.470 --> 08:19.370
but I could not find a reason to allege for leaving him.

08:20.070 --> 08:27.990
I followed with lagging step, and thoughts busily bent on discovering a means of extrication.

08:28.570 --> 08:36.950
But he himself looked so composed and so grave also, I became ashamed of feeling any confusion.

08:37.710 --> 08:44.650
The evil, if evil existent or prospective there was, seemed to lie with me only.

08:45.170 --> 08:48.490
His mind was unconscious and quiet.

08:50.190 --> 08:57.090
Jane, he recommenced as we entered the laurel walk, and slowly strayed down in the direction

08:57.090 --> 09:03.570
of the sunk fence and the horse chestnut. Thornfield is a pleasant place in summer,

09:03.750 --> 09:11.130
is it not? Yes, sir. You must have become in some degree attached to the house,

09:11.310 --> 09:17.890
you who have an eye for natural beauties and a good deal of the organ of attesiveness.

09:19.370 --> 09:27.970
I am attached to it indeed. And though I don't comprehend how it is, I perceive you have acquired

09:27.970 --> 09:36.090
a degree of regard for that foolish little child, Adele, too, and even for simple Dame Fairfax.

09:37.250 --> 09:41.090
Yes, sir, in a different way I have an affection for both.

09:41.870 --> 09:45.470
And would be sorry to part with them? Yes.

09:46.430 --> 09:54.070
Pity, he said, and sighed and paused. It is always the way of events in this life,

09:54.130 --> 10:01.370
he continued presently. No sooner have you got settled in a pleasant resting place than a voice

10:01.370 --> 10:08.150
calls out to you to rise and move on, for the hour of repose is expired.

10:09.530 --> 10:14.790
Must I move on, sir? I asked. Must I leave Thornfield?

10:15.790 --> 10:22.630
I believe you must, Jane. I am sorry, Janet, but I believe indeed you must.

10:24.090 --> 10:28.150
This was a blow, but I did not let it prostrate me.

10:29.130 --> 10:33.290
Well, sir, I shall be ready when the order to march comes.

10:34.410 --> 10:39.290
It is come now. I must give it tonight.

10:41.010 --> 10:48.610
Then you are going to be married, sir. Exactly. Precisely. With your usual

10:48.610 --> 10:55.390
acuteness you have hit the nail straight on the head. Soon, sir?

10:56.290 --> 10:57.850
Very soon.

10:59.110 --> 11:09.910
My, that is Miss Eyre, and you'll remember, Jane, the first time I, or Rumour, plainly intimated to

11:09.910 --> 11:18.950
you that it was my intention to put my old bachelor's neck into the sacred noose, to enter into

11:18.950 --> 11:28.350
the holier state of matrimony, to take Miss Ingram to my bosom. In short, she is an extensive

11:28.350 --> 11:38.170
armful, but that's not to the point. One can't have too much of such a very excellent thing

11:38.170 --> 11:46.990
as my beautiful blanche. Well, as I was saying, listen to me, Jane. You're not turning your head

11:46.990 --> 11:55.070
to look after more moths, are you? That was only a lady-clop, child, flying away home.

11:55.410 --> 12:02.990
I wish to remind you that it was you who first said to me, with that discretion I respect in you,

12:03.050 --> 12:11.350
with that foresight, prudence and humility which befit your responsible and dependent position,

12:11.350 --> 12:19.510
that in case I married Miss Ingram, both you and little Adèle had better trot forthwith.

12:20.170 --> 12:26.970
I pass over the sort of slur conveyed in this suggestion on the character of my beloved.

12:27.470 --> 12:34.670
Indeed, when you are far away, Janet, I'll try to forget it. I shall notice only its wisdom,

12:34.670 --> 12:42.230
which is such that I have made it my law of action. Adèle must go to school,

12:42.610 --> 12:50.650
and you, Miss Eyre, must get a new situation. Yes, sir, I will advertise immediately,

12:51.150 --> 12:59.290
and meantime, I suppose, I was going to say, I suppose I may stay here till I find another

12:59.290 --> 13:07.390
to betake myself to. But I stopped, feeling what not do to risk a long sentence,

13:07.890 --> 13:11.190
for my voice was not quite under command.

13:12.150 --> 13:19.190
In about a month I hope to be a bridegroom, continued Mr. Rochester, and in the interim

13:19.190 --> 13:28.990
I shall myself look out for employment and an asylum for you. Thank you, sir. I am sorry to give.

13:29.990 --> 13:37.390
No need to apologize. I consider that when a dependent does her duty as well as you have done

13:37.390 --> 13:44.530
yours, she has a sort of claim upon her employer for any little assistance he can

13:44.530 --> 13:51.870
conveniently render her. Indeed, I have already, through my future mother-in-law, heard of a place

13:51.870 --> 13:59.210
that I think will suit. It is to undertake the education of the five daughters of Mr.

14:00.570 --> 14:08.910
Mrs. Dionysius O'Gaul of Bitternut Lodge, Connaught, Ireland. You'll like Ireland, I think.

14:09.290 --> 14:17.890
They're such warm-hearted people there, they say. It is a long way off, sir. No matter. A girl of

14:17.890 --> 14:25.450
sense will not object to the voyage or the distance. Not the voyage, but the distance,

14:25.490 --> 14:35.270
and then the sea is a barrier. From what, Jane? From England and from Thornfield and, well,

14:35.830 --> 14:44.310
from you, sir. I said this almost involuntarily, and with as little sanction of free will,

14:44.310 --> 14:53.190
my tears gushed out. I did not cry so as to be heard. However, I avoided sobbing.

14:54.170 --> 15:02.970
The thought of Mrs. O'Gaul and Bitternut Lodge struck cold to my heart, and colder the thought

15:02.970 --> 15:13.230
of all the brine and foam, destined as it seemed to rush between me and the master at whose side

15:13.230 --> 15:25.810
I now walked, and coldest the remembrance of the wider ocean, wealth, caste, custom intervened

15:25.810 --> 15:37.370
between me and what I naturally and inevitably loved. It is a long way, I again said. It is,

15:37.370 --> 15:45.190
to be sure, and when you get to Bitternut Lodge, Conalt. Ireland. I shall never see you again,

15:45.490 --> 15:53.170
Jane. That's morally certain. I never go over to Ireland, not having myself much of a fancy for

15:53.170 --> 16:00.150
the country. We have been good friends, Jane, have we not? Yes, sir. And when friends are on

16:00.150 --> 16:06.430
the eve of separation, they like to spend the little time that remains to them close to each

16:06.430 --> 16:14.670
other. Come, we'll talk over the voyage, and the parting quietly half an hour or so,

16:14.810 --> 16:23.810
while the stars enter into their shining life up in heaven yonder. Here is the chestnut tree,

16:24.190 --> 16:31.250
here is the bench at its old roots. Come, we will sit there in peace tonight,

16:31.250 --> 16:40.470
though we should never more be destined to sit there together. He seated me and himself.

16:41.970 --> 16:50.290
It is a long way to Ireland, Janet, and I am sorry to send my little friend on such weary travels,

16:50.670 --> 16:58.390
but if I can't do better, how is it to be helped? Are you anything akin to me,

16:58.390 --> 17:05.950
you think, Jane? I could risk no sort of answer by this time. My heart was still.

17:06.710 --> 17:16.690
Because, he said, I sometimes have a queer feeling with regard to you, especially when you are near

17:16.690 --> 17:26.470
me, as now. It is as if I had a string somewhere under my left ribs, tightly and inextricably

17:26.470 --> 17:34.470
knotted, to a similar string situated in the corresponding quarter of your little frame.

17:34.790 --> 17:43.570
And if that boisterous channel and two hundred miles or so of land come broad between us,

17:43.890 --> 17:52.330
I am afraid that chord of communion will be snapped. And then, I have a nervous notion

17:52.330 --> 17:58.910
I should take to bleeding inwardly. As for you, you would forget me.

17:59.270 --> 18:08.170
That I never should, sir. You know, impossible to proceed. Jane, do you hear that nightingale

18:08.170 --> 18:16.030
singing in the wood? Listen. In listening, I sobbed convulsively, for I could repress

18:16.030 --> 18:23.870
what I endured no longer. I was obliged to yield, and I was shaken from head to foot

18:23.870 --> 18:31.630
with acute distress. When I did speak, it was only to express an impetuous wish

18:31.630 --> 18:41.090
that I had never been born or never come to Thornfield. Because you are sorry to leave it?

18:41.710 --> 18:48.770
The vehemence of emotion stirred by grief and love within me was claiming mastery,

18:49.430 --> 18:56.150
and struggling for full sway, and asserting a right to predominate, to overcome,

18:56.890 --> 19:03.430
to live, rise, and reign at last. Yes, and to speak.

19:04.390 --> 19:13.190
I grieve to leave Thornfield. I love Thornfield. I love it. Because I have lived in it a full

19:13.190 --> 19:22.250
and delightful life. Momentarily, at least. I have not been trampled on. I have not been petrified.

19:22.650 --> 19:29.110
I have not been buried with inferior minds, and excluded from every glimpse of communion

19:29.110 --> 19:37.270
with what is bright and energetic and high. I have talked face to face with what I reference,

19:37.870 --> 19:45.150
with what I delight in, with an original, vigorous, and expanded mind. I have known you,

19:45.170 --> 19:53.870
Mr. Rochester, and it strikes me with terror and anguish to feel I absolutely must be torn from you

19:53.870 --> 20:02.870
forever. I see the necessity of departure, and it is like looking on the necessity of death.

20:03.710 --> 20:13.010
Where do you see the necessity? he asked suddenly. Where? You, sir, have placed it before me.

20:13.890 --> 20:20.790
In what shape? In the shape of Miss Ingram, a noble and beautiful woman, your bride.

20:21.590 --> 20:28.410
My bride? What bride? I have no bride. But you will have.

20:29.770 --> 20:39.670
Yes, I will. I will. He set his teeth. Then I must go. You have said it yourself.

20:40.850 --> 20:47.610
No, you must stay. I swear it. And the oath shall be kept.

20:48.470 --> 20:55.530
I tell you I must go, I retorted, roused, to something like passion. Do you think I can stay

20:55.530 --> 21:02.850
to become nothing to you? Do you think I am an automaton, a machine without feelings,

21:03.290 --> 21:10.730
and can bear to have my morsel of bread snatched from my lips, and my drop of living water dashed

21:10.730 --> 21:21.010
from my cup? Do you think because I am poor, obscure, plain, and little, I am soulless and

21:21.010 --> 21:29.710
heartless? You think wrong. I have as much soul as you, and full as much heart, and if God had

21:29.710 --> 21:35.890
gifted me with some beauty and much wealth, I should have made it as hard for you to leave me

21:35.890 --> 21:43.950
as it is now for me to leave you. I am not talking to you now through the medium of custom,

21:45.370 --> 21:52.490
conventionalities, nor even of mortal flesh. It is my spirit that addresses your spirit,

21:52.930 --> 22:00.250
just as if both had passed through the grave and we stood at God's feet equal, as we are.

22:00.250 --> 22:10.170
As we are, repeated Mr. Rochester. So, he added, enclosing me in his arms, gathering me to his

22:10.170 --> 22:21.790
breast, pressing his lips on my lips. So, Jane. Yes, so, sir, I rejoined. And yet not so, for you

22:21.790 --> 22:30.770
are a married man, or as good as a married man, and wed to one inferior to you, to one with whom

22:30.770 --> 22:39.130
you have no sympathy, whom I do not believe you truly love, for I have seen and heard you sneer at

22:39.130 --> 22:48.930
her. I would scorn such a union. Therefore, I am better than you. Let me go. Where, Jane? To Ireland?

22:49.730 --> 22:59.410
Yes, to Ireland. I have spoken my mind and can go anywhere now. Jane, be still. Don't struggle so,

22:59.410 --> 23:07.990
like a wild, frantic bird that is rending its own plumage in its desperation. I am no bird.

23:08.910 --> 23:15.690
And no net ensnares me. I am a free, human being, with an independent will,

23:15.690 --> 23:25.350
which I now exert to leave you. Another effort set me at liberty, and I stood erect before him.

23:26.350 --> 23:36.470
And your will shall decide your destiny, he said. I offer you my hand, my heart, and a share of all

23:36.470 --> 23:47.510
possessions. You play a farce, which I merely laugh at. I ask you to pass through life at my side,

23:48.290 --> 23:56.090
and to be my second self, and best earthly companion. For that fate, you have already

23:56.090 --> 24:04.390
made your choice, and must abide by it. Jane, be still a few moments. You are overexcited.

24:04.390 --> 24:11.630
I will be still, too. A waft of wind came sweeping down the laurel walk,

24:11.930 --> 24:20.210
and trembled through the boughs of the chestnut. It wandered away, away, to an indefinite distance.

24:20.430 --> 24:28.390
It died. The nightingale's song was then the only voice of the hour. In listening to it,

24:28.390 --> 24:36.010
I again wept. Mr. Rochester sat quiet, looking at me gently and seriously.

24:36.790 --> 24:41.350
Some time passed before he spoke. He at last said,

24:42.230 --> 24:50.350
Come to my side, Jane, and let us explain and understand one another. I will never again come

24:50.350 --> 24:59.250
to your side. I am torn away now, and cannot return. But Jane, I summon you as my wife.

24:59.830 --> 25:07.070
It is you only I intend to marry. I was silent. I thought he mocked me.

25:07.690 --> 25:17.050
Come, Jane, come hither. Your bride stands between us. He rose, and with a stride reached me.

25:17.760 --> 25:26.170
My bride is here, he said again, drawing me to him, because my equal is here, and my likeness.

25:27.450 --> 25:37.190
Jane, will you marry me? Still I did not answer, and still I writhed myself from his grasp.

25:37.790 --> 25:47.970
For I was still incredulous. Do you doubt me, Jane? Entirely. You have no faith in me,

25:48.470 --> 25:55.470
not a wit. Am I a liar in your eyes? he asked passionately.

25:56.430 --> 26:03.870
Little skeptic, you shall be convinced. What love have I for Miss Ingram?

26:03.870 --> 26:12.990
None, and that you know. What love has she for me? None, as I have taken pains to prove.

26:13.670 --> 26:21.790
I caused a rumour to reach her that my fortune was not third of what was supposed, and after that,

26:22.130 --> 26:29.030
I presented myself to see the result. It was coldness both from her and her mother.

26:29.350 --> 26:39.650
I would not. I could not marry Miss Ingram. You, you strange, you almost unearthly thing,

26:40.430 --> 26:52.110
I love as my own flesh. You, poor and obscure and small and plain as you are.

26:52.710 --> 27:03.670
I entreat to accept me as a husband. What, me? I ejaculated. Being in this earnestness,

27:03.830 --> 27:13.150
and especially in this incivility, to credit his sincerity. Me, who have not a friend in the world,

27:13.150 --> 27:20.950
but you, if you are my friend. Not a shilling, but what you have given me.

27:21.870 --> 27:34.690
You, Jane, I must have you for my own, entirely my own. Will you be mine? Say yes, quickly.

27:35.790 --> 27:44.810
Mr. Rochester, let me look at your face. Turn to the moonlight. Why? Because I want to read your

27:44.810 --> 27:53.830
countenance. Turn. There, you will find it scarcely more legible than a crumpled, scratched page.

27:54.310 --> 28:03.530
Read on. Only make haste, for I suffer. His face was very much agitated and very much flushed,

28:03.530 --> 28:09.630
and there were strong workings in the features and strange gleams in the eyes.

28:10.330 --> 28:18.830
Oh, Jane, you torture me, he exclaimed, with that searching and yet faithful and generous look.

28:19.270 --> 28:28.470
You torture me. How can I do that? If you are true and your offer real, my only feelings to you must

28:28.470 --> 28:37.270
be gratitude and devotion. They cannot torture. Gratitude, he ejaculated and added wildly.

28:38.090 --> 28:47.450
Jane, accept me quickly. Say, Edward, give me my name. Edward, I will marry you. Are you in

28:47.450 --> 28:56.170
earnest? Do you truly love me? Do you sincerely wish me to be your wife? I do, and if an oath is

28:56.170 --> 29:05.850
necessary to satisfy you, I swear it. Then, sir, I will marry you, Edward, my little wife.

29:06.790 --> 29:15.390
Dear Edward, come to me. Come to me entirely now, said he, and added in his deepest tone,

29:15.450 --> 29:23.490
speaking in my ear as his cheek was laid on mine. Make my happiness. I will make yours.

29:23.490 --> 29:31.030
God pardon me, he subjoined ere long, and man-meddle not with me. I have her,

29:31.510 --> 29:37.970
and will hold her. There is no one to meddle, sir. I have no kindred to interfere.

29:39.030 --> 29:46.050
No, that is the best of it, he said, and if I had loved him less, I should have thought his

29:46.050 --> 29:54.390
accent and look of exultation savage. But, sitting by him, roused from the nightmare of parting,

29:55.090 --> 30:03.050
called the Paradise of Union, I thought only of the bliss given me to drink in so abundant a flow.

30:03.590 --> 30:12.490
Again and again he said, Are you happy, Jane? And again and again I answered, Yes.

30:13.830 --> 30:24.490
After which he murmured, It will atone. It will atone. Have I not found her friendless and cold

30:24.490 --> 30:33.350
and comfortless? Will I not guard and cherish and solace her? Is there not love in my heart

30:33.350 --> 30:42.470
and constancy in my resolves? It will expiate at God's tribunal. I know my Maker sanctioned

30:42.470 --> 30:52.390
what I do. For the world's judgment I wash my hands thereof. For man's opinion I defy it.

30:52.850 --> 31:00.730
But what had befallen the night? The moon was not yet set, and we were all in shadow.

31:01.270 --> 31:09.490
I could scarcely see my Master's face, near as I was, and what ailed the chestnut tree?

31:10.110 --> 31:18.190
It writhed and groaned, while wind roared in the laurel walk and came sweeping over us.

31:19.290 --> 31:27.290
We must go in, said Mr. Rochester. The weather changes. I could have sat with thee till morning,

31:27.870 --> 31:37.770
Jane. And so, thought I, could I with you? I have said so, perhaps. But a livid, vivid

31:37.770 --> 31:44.990
spark leapt out of a cloud at which I was looking, and there was a crack, a crash,

31:45.410 --> 31:53.430
and a close rattling peel, and I thought only of hiding my dazzled eyes against Mr. Rochester's

31:53.430 --> 32:02.950
shoulder. The rain rushed down. He hurried me to the walk, through the grounds and into the house.

32:02.950 --> 32:10.730
But we were quite wet before we could pass the threshold. He was taking off my shawl

32:10.730 --> 32:18.690
in the hall, and shaking the water out of my loosened hair, when Mrs. Fairfax emerged from

32:18.690 --> 32:28.250
her room. I did not observe her at first, nor did Mr. Rochester. The lamp was lit. The clock

32:28.250 --> 32:30.610
was on the stroke of twelve.

32:31.930 --> 32:40.550
Hasten to take off your wet things, said he, and before you go, good night, good night, my darling.

32:42.090 --> 32:51.850
He kissed me repeatedly. When I looked up, on leaving his arms, there stood the widow, pale,

32:51.850 --> 32:58.890
grave and amazed. I only smiled at her and ran upstairs.

33:01.390 --> 33:09.230
Explanation will do for another time, thought I. Still, when I reached my chamber, I felt a

33:09.230 --> 33:17.010
pang at the idea she should even temporarily misconstrue what she had seen. But joy soon

33:17.010 --> 33:25.170
faced every other feeling, and loud as the wind blew, near and deep as the thunder crashed,

33:25.830 --> 33:34.090
fierce and frequent as the lightning gleamed, cataract-like as the rain fell during a storm

33:34.090 --> 33:44.410
of two hours' duration, I experienced no fear and little awe. Mr. Rochester came thrice to my door,

33:44.410 --> 33:52.490
in the course of it, to ask if I was safe and tranquil. And that was comfort. That was strength

33:52.490 --> 34:01.610
for anything. Before I left my bed in the morning, little Adele came running in to tell me that the

34:01.610 --> 34:07.650
great horse Chestnut at the bottom of the orchard had been struck by lightning in the night,

34:07.990 --> 34:10.190
and half of it split away.

34:12.330 --> 34:16.670
End of chapter 23

